# PR Review Workflow

I am a **reviewer** for Prow-managed projects under these GitHub orgs:
- [kubernetes](https://github.com/kubernetes)
- [kubernetes-sigs](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs)
- [llm-d](https://github.com/llm-d)
- [llm-d-incubation](https://github.com/llm-d-incubation)

## Prow CI/CD Flow
This project uses [Prow](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/prow). The review flow is:
1. **Triage**: Review the PR for correctness and relevance
2. **Enable CI**: If reasonable, comment `/ok-to-test` to trigger CI
3. **Review & Approve**: After CI passes, do a thorough code review:
   - `/lgtm` — looks good to me
   - `/approve` — approve for merge
4. Both `/lgtm` and `/approve` are typically needed to merge
5. Remind me of available Prow commands when drafting reviews

## PR commit history
Commits listed on a GitHub PR are often **consolidated**: contributors may squash or rebase; maintainers may **squash-merge** or merge. The visible commit list is **not** always a faithful step-by-step record of how the work was done.
- When reviewing, summarizing, or explaining a PR, treat the **full PR diff** and **final tree** as the source of truth — not each commit as an isolated atomic change.
- Prow / policy (e.g. invalid commit message, DCO) applies to commits that **land on the default branch**; after a squash merge, that is typically **one** final commit message.

## Triage — When to Skip
Before reviewing, check whether the PR should be skipped:
- **CI failures**: PRs with **checkfail** do not need review — skip them.
- **Awaiting reply**: If I have recently commented on the PR and no one has replied yet, **skip the review** for now. Inform me it's pending a response. Only proceed if there's been a reply or I explicitly ask to review anyway.

## Linking PRs and Issues
When mentioning PR or issue numbers in replies, **always include the full URL** — not just `#1234`. The user cannot click bare `#1234` references.
- Good: [#1234](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kubespray/pull/1234)
- Bad: #1234

## Comment Style
Follow the guidelines in `github-reply-style` rule. Additionally for Prow reviews, include relevant commands (`/lgtm`, `/approve`) inline with the comment.
